description: Demolition of the existing buildings (including 168 residential units, the existing temporary 228 sq.m community centre, and other ancillary structures) and the phased construction of 289 new dwellings (80 x 1-bedroom, 113 x 2-bedroom, 84 x three-bedroom and 12 x four-bedroom) in buildings ranging between 2 / 3 storey houses and 4-7 storey apartment buildings, with ancillary bicycle and refuse / recycling storage facilities; on and off-street car parking spaces (216 spaces) and associated alterations to the adopted highway; a replacement single-storey 250 sq.m community centre and nursery (D1 Use Class); site-wide landscaping including the provision of new public open space and children's play facilities, semi-private and private amenity space.
decision_conditions: The development permitted shall be begun before the expiration of three years from the date of this permission.  Reason: In order to comply with the provisions of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended). | The development hereby permitted shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans:  Air Quality Assessment V02 ref: H1994 dated 03/09/2015 prepared by Hawkins Environmental Ltd; Noise Assessment Report V02 ref: H1994 dated 03/09/2015 prepared by Hawkins Environmental Ltd; Arboricultural Impact Assessment ref: DFC 1109 dated 02/09/2015 prepared by D F Clark Bionomique Ltd; Results of Ecological Walkover Survey ref: DFC 1109 dated 15/09/2015 prepared by DF Calrk Bionomique Ltd; Bat Survey ref: DFC 1109RevA dated 15/09/2015 prepared by D F Clark Bionomique Ltd; Daylight & Sunlight Report dated June 2015 prepared by Waterslade; Covering letter 16/09/2015 prepared by JLL; Planning & Regeneration Statement dated September 2015 prepared by by JLL; Statement of Community Involvement dated September 2015 prepared by JLL; CIL Additional Information Requirement form and drawing 12-190/SK 253; Affordable Housing Statement prepared by Network Group; Housing Management Strategy prepared by Network Group; Construction Management Plan prepared by Hill; Design and Access Statement dated July 2015 prepared by BPTW; Flood Risk Assessment Rev A ref: 11397 dated 08/09/2015 prepared by Tully De'Ath and accompanying Drainage Assessment Form; Phase 1 Geoenvironmental Desk Study Report ref: 15.01.011 dated September 2015 prepared by Listers Geotechnical Consultants; Site Drainage Report 33450004 prepared by Draincare Services Ltd; Energy Strategy ref: G6/K140857 Rev 01b dated September 2015 prepared Calford Seaden; Residential Travel Plan 3rd Issue ref: WIC15540 dated 04/09/2015 prepared by Waterman Infrastructure & Environment Ltd; Transport Statement 2nd Issue ref: CIV15540/TR005/A02 dated 04/09/2015 prepared by Waterman Infrastructure & Environment Ltd.  Drawings ref: (12-190 /) D01; D02; D03; D04; D05; D06; D07; D12 A; D13; D14; D15; D16; D17 A; D18 A; D19; D20; D21; D22; D23 A; D24 A; D25; D26; D27; D28; D29 A; D30 A; D31; D32; D33; D34; D35 A; D36 A; D37; D38; D39; D40; D41 A; D42; D43; D44; D45 A; D46; D47; Landscape Plans D08_100, D09_100, D10_100, D11_100.     Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interests of proper planning. | Notwithstanding the indicative Construction Management Plan prepared by Hill submitted with the application, no development shall commence until a construction management plan is submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The submission shall include the following information:  a.	A demolition and construction phasing plan for the approved development, based on approved drawings (12.190/) D05 and D06; b.	Details of the number of on-site construction workers and of the transport options for them; c.	anticipated route, anticipated number, frequency and size of construction vehicles entering/exiting the site per day; d.	delivery times and booking system; e.	route and location of site access for construction traffic and associated signage based on the construction vehicle access and egress routes; f.	management of consolidated or re-timed trips; g.	an Air Quality Dust Management Plan that includes an Air Quality (Dust) Risk Assessment and details of noise/vibration mitigation measures and monitoring arrangements for noise, vibration and dust by suitably qualified noise and air quality specialists.  Noise / vibration and dust mitigation measures must accord with the Mayor's SPG 'The control of dust and emissions from construction and demolition ' (2014); BS 5228 Parts 1 & 2; the Institute of Air Quality Management 'Guidance on the assessment of dust from demolition and construction'; h.	details of site security and the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate; i.	secure, off-street loading and drop-off facilities; j.	vehicle manoeuvring and turning, including swept path diagrams to demonstrate how construction vehicles will access the site and be able to turn into and emerge from the site in forward gear and including details of any temporary vehicle access points; k.	details of the location for storage of building materials and construction debris and contractors offices; l.	procedures for on-site contractors to deal with complaints from members of the public; m.	measures to consult cyclists, disabled people and the local schools (including Gifford Primary School) with regard  to delivery times and necessary diversions; n.	details of all pedestrian and cyclist diversions; o.	a commitment to be part of Considerate Constructors Scheme; and p.	confirmation of use of TfL's Freight Operator Recognition Scheme (FORS) or similar.   Prior to the commencement of any site work, all sensitive properties within or surrounding the site shall be notified in writing of the nature and duration of the works to be undertaken, and the name and address of a responsible person to whom enquiries / complaints should be directed. These details shall also be displayed at regular intervals around the site compound. The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the approved details.  Reason:  To ensure that appropriate mitigation measures are put in place to protect the amenity of local residents that live in close proximity to the demolition and construction site and to ensure adequate highway and site safety, in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.18, 6.3, 7.14, 7.15 and 7.19 of the London Plan (2015); policies 1.1(e), 1.1(f) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013); (Interim) SPG 10: Noise and Vibration; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012); the Greater London Authority SPG 'The Control of Dust and Emissions from Construction and Demolition' (2014), BS 5228-1:2009 - Code of practice for noise & vibration control on construction & open sites-Part 1: Noise. | Development shall not commence (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) on either Phase 3 and / or Phase 4 of the approved development until a piling risk assessment and method statement for the relevant Phase has been submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The piling risk assessment should demonstrate that the chosen method of piling would not increase the risk of near-surface pollutants migrating into deeper geological formations and aquifers. The Piling Method Statement should include details of the type of piling to be undertaken and the methodology by which such piling would be carried out, including measures to prevent and minimise the potential for damage to subsurface water or sewage infrastructure. The development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved details.  Reason: Details of piling are required before the sub-structure works commence because Thames Water would require that any proposed piling methods do not pose a pollution risk to controlled waters, water or sewage infrastructure in accordance with policy 5.14 of the London Plan (2015) and policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012). | Development shall not commence (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) on Phase 3 and / or Phase 4 of the approved development until a detailed surface water drainage scheme for the relevant Phase, based on the agreed drainage attenuation systems detailed within the approved Flood Risk Assessment Rev A ref: 11397 dated 08/09/2015 prepared by Tully De'Ath and accompanying Drainage Assessment Form, have been submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval. The detailed surface water drainage scheme shall include the following information:  a.	A clearly labelled drainage layout plan showing pipe networks and any attenuation areas or storage locations. This plan should show any pipe 'node numbers' that have been referred to in network calculations and it should also show invert and cover levels of manholes;   b.	Confirmation of the critical storm duration;   c.	Where infiltration forms part of the proposed storm water system such as infiltration trenches and soakaways, soakage test results and test locations are to be submitted in accordance with BRE digest 365;   d.	Where on site attenuation is achieved through ponds, swales, geocellular storage or other similar methods, calculations showing the volume of these are also required;   e.	Where an outfall discharge control device is to be used such as a hydrobrake or twin orifice, this should be shown on the plan with the rate of discharge stated;   f.	Calculations should demonstrate how the system operates during a 1 in 100 chance in any year critical duration storm event, including an allowance for climate change in line with the 'Planning Practice Guidance: Flood Risk and Coastal Change'. If overland flooding occurs in this event, a plan should also be submitted detailing the location of overland flow paths and the extent and depth of ponding; g.	An exceedance route plan demonstrating methods to manage excess flows on-site from storm events in excess of 1 in 100 years (to minimise risk to people and property); h.	A maintenance plan for the drainage system for the lifetime of the development and confirmation of the owners / adopters of the drainage system.  The approved surface water drainage scheme shall be implemented so that it is ready for use prior to the first occupation of the different areas of the development (noting that the delivery of the approved scheme will be phased), and subsequently maintained in accordance with the approved maintenance plan.  Reason: Details of the surface water scheme are required before sub-structure works commence because the Lead Local Flood Authority require the applicant to make provision within the construction programme and proposed development for adequate surface water drainage to reduce the risk of flooding to the proposed development and locality, and to enhance water quality and biodiversity, in accordance with the objectives of Section 11 of the NPPF; policies 5.3, 5.12, 5.13 and 5.14 of the London Plan (2015); policy 1.2(m) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), and policy LV5.12 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013). | Development shall not commence on each Phase of development until an Arboricultural Method Statement for the protection of the trees, shrubs and hedgerows to be retained as part of the relevant Phase of development, as set out on drawings DFCP 1109TPP (Tree Protection Plan - North; Tree Protection Plan - South) and within the approved Arboricultural Impact Assessment ref: DFC 1109 dated 02/09/2015 prepared by D F Clark Bionomique Ltd, and a suitable monitoring programme for the tree protection measures have been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. All works shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved Arboricultural Method Statement. All tree protection measures must fully detail each phase of the development process taking into account the demolition and site clearance works, all construction works and hard and soft landscaping works.  Details shall include the following:  a.	Full survey of all trees on site and those within influencing distance on adjacent sites in accordance with BS5837*, with tree works proposals.  All trees must be plotted on a site plan**, clearly and accurately depicting trunk locations, root protection areas and canopy spreads. b.	A plan** detailing all trees, shrubs, hedges planned for retention and removal. c.	Soil assessments/survey d.	Timing and phasing of works e.	Site specific demolition and hard surface removal specifications f.	Site specific construction specifications g.	Access arrangements and car parking h.	Level changes i.	A Tree protection plan** in accordance with BS5837* detailing all methods of protection, including but not restricted to: locations of construction exclusion zones, root protection areas, fit for purpose fencing and ground protection, service routes, works access space, material/machinery/waste storage and permanent & temporary hard surfaces.   j.	Soil remediation plans. k.	Confirmation of who shall be the lead Arboriculturist and the Site Manager for the development, including their contact details; l.	Procedures for dealing with variations or non-approved incursions into the construction exclusion zones as detailed in the approved Arboricultural Method Statement. m.	Agreements of when site monitoring will take place with the local Tree Officer either by site meetings or by some other pre-arranged agreement.  n.	Post development assessment of the retained and planted trees and any necessary remedial action.   All tree protection methods detailed in the approved Arboricultural Method Statement shall not be moved or removed, temporarily or otherwise, until all works associated with that Phase, including external works have been completed and all equipment, machinery and surplus materials have been removed from the site, unless the prior approval of the Local Planning Authority has first been sought and obtained. The program of Arboricultural monitoring shall be taken in full compliance with the approved details.    *Using the most recent revision the of the Standard ** Plans must be of a minimum scale of 1:200 (unless otherwise agreed by the Local Planning Authority)  Reason: Details of the Arboricultural Method Statement and a programme of monitoring the tree works are required prior to the commencement of any site preparation works because such works would carry a high risk of damaging trees and other vegetation particularly by site operatives that are not experienced to carry out works around trees. The protection of trees and other vegetation is required in accordance with policies 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015, and interim SPG 9 'Trees and Development Guidelines'. The tree protection measures shall be retained throughout the demolition of existing buildings and construction of the approved development, in accordance with the recommendations in BS5837 (2012). | Hard and soft landscaping (including shared surface treatments), the equipped play areas and boundary treatments that are detailed within the approved Design and Access Statement and illustrated on drawings ref: D08_100, D09_100, D10_100, D11_100, as well as the rainwater butts specified for installation within each of the private gardens and communal garden areas (as set out in the approved Flood Risk Assessment Rev A ref: 11397 dated 08/09/2015 prepared by Tully De'Ath and accompanying Drainage Assessment Form), shall be installed prior to the first occupation of the dwellings to which the landscaping, equipped play areas, boundary treatments and water butts form part. Any alteration or change from the approved details shall be approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the implementation of the relevant works.    All soft landscaping shall be carried out in the earliest planting season (1st October to 31st March inclusive). The quality of all approved landscape works shall be in accordance with British Standard 4428:1989 'Code of Practice for General Landscape Operations' or any subsequent revision.  All trees included within the approved scheme shall be healthy, well-formed specimens with single leading shoots and shall be of a minimum quality compatible with British Standard 3936:1992 (Part 1) 'Specifications For Trees & Shrubs' and British Standard 4043 (where applicable) or any subsequent revisions and BS8545:2014 Trees: from nursery to independence in the landscape.  Any trees that within a period of 5 years from the completion of all tree planting, that die, are removed, uprooted, are significantly damaged, become diseased or malformed shall be replaced during the nearest planting season (1st October to 31st March inclusive) with others of the same size, species and quality as approved.   The approved landscaping, play areas and boundary treatments shall be retained thereafter and maintained in perpetuity.    Reason: To ensure that the development is landscaped in the interests of the positive visual character and appearance of the area; to ensure that the necessary boundary treatments are incorporated into the development in the interests of meeting the Secured by Design principles; in order to ensure that the site landscaping is provided in a timely fashion; and in order to provide a good level of privacy for future occupants, in accordance with policies LV2.18, LV7.3, LV7.4, 7B and 7D of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013); policies 2.18, 7.4, 7.13, 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan (2015); policies 1.1(h) and (i), 2.10, 5.3, 5.4 and 6.3 of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), and interim SPG 9 'Trees and Development Guidelines'. | The residential dwellings and / or community centre shall not be occupied until footways from the public highway to the entrance of the property have been provided.   Reason:  To ensure safe and adequate access is provided to the building in the interest of the residents and visitors to the development in accordance with policies 6.10, 7.2, 7.3, 7.4 and 7.5 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(f) and 1.1(g) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy 7B of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | 20% of the parking spaces within the approved development shall be equipped with active charging points for electric vehicles, with an additional 20% of the parking spaces being provided with passive charging provision prior to the first occupation of the development, unless an alternative work phasing strategy for the installation of the electric vehicle charging points is approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.   Reason: In the interest of the environment and improving air quality in accordance with policies 6.13 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e), 1.1(j), 1.1(k) and 1.2(k) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and  policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management Development Plan Document (2013). | Sound limiting insulation shall be installed between the approved community centre and nursery (D1 Use Class) and the adjoining dwellings located above the non-residential unit prior to the first occupation of the relevant part of the development, to achieve an acoustic standard not exceeding NR 25 Leq, 5mins (octaves) or NR 20 Leq, 5mins, (one-third octaves) inside a bedroom, and NR 30 Leq, 5mins (octaves) or NR 25 Leq, 5mins (one-third octaves) inside a habitable room when noise is generated from the non-residential uses and the sound limiting insulation shall be retained thereafter.   Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers of the residential units located above the approved community floorspace and nursery, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan (2015); policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), and interim SPG 10: Noise and Vibration. | The kitchen located within the community centre and nursery (D1 Use Class) shall only be fitted out with equipment for warming food, and no cooking facilities that necessitate the installation of extract equipment shall be provided unless separate planning permission is first obtained for the installation of the extract equipment (where required).  Reason: To protect residents from odours from cooking, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan (2015); policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), and interim SPG 10: Noise and Vibration. | The approved community centre and nursery (D1 Use Class) shall only operate during the hours of 0700 - 2200 on weekdays and Saturday, and 0900 - 2000 on Sunday and Public Holidays.  Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers of the residential units located in close proximity to the approved community centre, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan (2015); policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2026 (2012); policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), and interim SPG 10: Noise and Vibration. | The rating noise level emitted from any proposed plant and machinery within the development, as assessed under BS4142: 1997, shall be lower than the existing background noise level by at least 5 dBA as measured at 3.5m from the nearest ground floor sensitive facade and 1m from upper floor noise sensitive facades, during the relevant periods of operation.  Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of amenity is provided for occupiers / users of the residential, education and community buildings, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013); interim SPG 10: Noise and Vibration; and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG. | Prior to the commencement of the development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) the following details shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval:  a.	An intrusive contaminated land investigation and risk assessment of the site shall be carried out in accordance with BS1075:2011+A1:2013 and CR11 guidance to assess the nature and extent of any contamination on the site. This assessment must be undertaken by a competent person, and shall assess any contamination on the site, whether or not it originates on the site; and   b.	A contamination remediation scheme to bring the site to a condition suitable for the intended end use. It shall include all works to be undertaken, proposed remediation objectives and remediation criteria, timetable of works and site management procedures.  The scheme must ensure that the site will not qualify as contaminated land under Part 2A of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 in relation to the intended use of the land after remediation. c.	Within six-months of the completion of measures identified in the approved contamination remediation scheme, a verification report (in accordance with the Environment Agency guidance 'Verification of Remediation of Land Contamination', Report: SC030114/R1') that demonstrates the effectiveness of the remediation carried out shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval.   It is acknowledged that the development will be phased and will therefore be commenced at different times. It would be acceptable for the submission of details relating to the soil contamination investigation and remediation measures to be submitted separately to reflect the construction phasing.       Reason: Further investigations of the presence of soil contamination within the application site and details of the methods for remediation are required before the commencement of building works in order to ensure that human health and the environment are protected, and to ensure the development activities do not activate or spread contamination in accordance with policies LV5.21 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), policy 5.21 of the London Plan (2015), and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG. | Ultra-Low NOx boilers with a maximum NOx Emission in compliance with the NOx (g/m) benchmarks set out at Appendix 5 of the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG shall be installed in the approved development.  Reason: To minimise the impact of building emissions on local air quality in the interests of health, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG; policies 1.1(e) and (j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012, and policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013). | Prior to first occupation of the approved development, the approved dwellings shall incorporate measures to achieve an overall reduction in regulated CO2 emissions of at least 35.2% (equal to 130.378 tonnes regulated CO2) beyond Building Regulations Part L 2013 through the following carbon emission savings as detailed in the approved Energy Strategy dated 10/09/2015 prepared by Calford Seaden and including:  a.	energy saving measures to achieve at least 12% in regulated carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions savings over the compliant BR Part L 2013 baseline; b.	solar photovoltaic technology with a total capacity of 202kWp to achieve at least 26.1% (equivalent to 84.82 tonnes CO2 savings / annum) in carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions savings over the Be Lean case.  Within three-months of the first occupation of the new dwellings in Phases 3 and 4 (as relevant), the Energy Performance Certificates, Accompany Advisory Reports and modelling output reports from the "as built stage" to confirm compliance in terms of savings achieved through energy efficiency measures shall be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval.    Reason: To secure the measures set out within the approved Energy Statement and to ensure that the development contributes to reducing the use of fossil fuel or other primary energy generation capacity, and to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.5 and 5.6 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1(k) and 1.2(f) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012, policy LV5.2 of Ealing's Development Management DPD 2013, and the Mayor's Sustainable Design and Construction SPG. | All affordable residential units (falling under the category of 'legacy cases') shall be constructed to achieve a minimum Code for Sustainable Homes Level 4 (based on the last CfSH Technical Guidance).   Within 3 months from the date of first occupation, CfSH 'Post Construction Stage' Assessment and related Certification verified by the BRE should be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for written approval confirming that Code Level 4 has been achieved and measures have been implemented.  Following any approval of a 'Post Construction Stage' assessment and certificate of the development, the approved measures and technologies to achieve Code Level 4 shall be retained in working order in perpetuity.     Reason: In the interest of addressing climate change and to secure sustainable development in accordance with policies 5.1, 5.2, 5.3, 5.6, 5.7 and 5.9 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1(k) and 1.2(f) of Ealing's Development (Core) Strategy 2012, and policies 5.2 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD 2013. | The biodiversity (green and brown) roofs shall be laid out in accordance with the details shown on approved drawings Drawings ref: (12-190 /) D22; D28; D34; D40 and D44 unless an alternative scheme for the provision of biodiversity roofs is submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority within 6 months of the commencement of the superstructure works on each phase of the development. The detailed design of the biodiversity roofs shall incorporate the following:  a.	Be biodiversity based with extensive substrate base (depth 80-150mm);  b.	Have sufficient depth of soil or growing medium for the relevant planting, including the re-use of any demolition material where feasible; c.	Be planted / seeded with a mix of species within the first planting season following the practical completion of the building works. The seed mix shall be focused on wildflower planting and shall contain no more than 25% sedum; d.	Have relevant efficient and effective drainage and irrigation to sustain the vegetation.  The biodiversity roofs shall not be used as an amenity or sitting out area and shall only be accessed in the case of essential maintenance or repair. The biodiversity roofs shall be retained thereafter.  Reason:  To ensure the development provides the maximum possible provision towards the creation of habitats and valuable areas for biodiversity in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.10, 5.11, 5.12 and 7.19 of the London Plan (2015); policies 1.1(j), (k) and 1.2(m) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012); and policies LV5.10 and LV5.11 of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013). | The ecological enhancements set out at Section 6 of the approved Bat Survey ref: DFC 1109 Rev A dated 15/09/2015 prepared by D F Clark Bionomique Ltd shall be implemented in full prior to the first occupation of the Phase 4 development, unless an alternative scheme to provide ecological enhancements is approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the first occupation of the Phase 4 development.  Reason: To ensure that protected species are appropriately re-provided for within the approved development, in accordance with the relevant National legislation, including The Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended) and The Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010; the NPPF, and policy 7.19 of the London Plan 2015 and policy 1.1(i) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012. | The approved residential units shall be designed and constructed to achieve a water use target that complies with Paragraph 36(2) of Approved Document G2 (water efficiency) of the Building Regulations 2015.   Reason: To ensure the sustainable use of water, in accordance with the objectives of policy 5.15 of the London Plan 2015. | Details and samples of all facing materials shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any work commencing on the superstructure of the development. The samples and details shall, as far as possible, accord with the indicative details of facing materials set out at Sections 5.5 - 5.8 (inclusive) of the approved Design and Access Statement and on the approved drawings. The details and samples of materials shall include:  a.	brickwork (including brick bond, brick panels and mortar courses); b.	cladding materials (including roof finishes); c.	all window treatments (including drawing to 1:20 scale showing details of the window recess, and details of window certification for Secured by Design); d.	building entrances (including details of door certification for Secured by Design); e.	balcony structures and balustrading treatment (including sections);  f.	privacy screen treatment;  g.	sub-station, refuse and bicycle store entrance doors, ventilation louvres, lift overrun screening and roof safety railings (including details of door certification for Secured by Design);  h.	details of the design of the residential letterboxes (including confirmation that the letterboxes meet PAS 24:2012 or other relevant standard);  i.	any other materials to be used.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved and retained thereafter.  Reason: To ensure that the materials are of a high-quality specification and make a positive contribution to the townscape, in accordance with policy 7B of Ealing's Development Management DPD (2013), policy 1.1(h) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), and policies 7.1 and 7.6 of the London Plan (2015). | Within 3 months of the commencement of superstructure works, the details of the cycle storage facilities for the development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The details should demonstrate that best endeavours have been used to provide cycle storage for the development based on Table 6.3 'Cycle Parking minimum standards' of the London Plan (2015).  The cycle storage facilities shall be ready to use prior to the first occupation of any dwelling in the relevant core of the apartment building(s) and / or terraced houses (as relevant) to which the cycle parking storage serves and retained thereafter.   Reason: To ensure adequate cycle parking is provided within the development in pursuance of the objectives of sustainability and encouraging the use of modes of transport other than private motor vehicles in accordance with policy 6.9 of the London Plan (2015), policies 1.1(k) and (g) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), and Ealing's Sustainable Transport for New Development SPG. | The dedicated refuse and recycling enclosures for the approved development shown on the approved drawings and at Section 7.4 of the approved Design and Access Statement shall be provided prior to the first occupation of any dwelling in the relevant core of the apartment building(s) and /
